{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Charly Dörfel | image = Dörfel, Gert 10-11 WP.JPG | fullname = Gert Dörfel | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1939|9|18}} | birth_place = [[Hamburg]], Germany | height = {{height|m=1.70|precision=0}} | position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]], [[Forward (association football)#Winger|winger]] | currentclub = | clubnumber = | youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}–1958 | youthclubs1 = PSV Hamburg | youthyears2 = 1958–1960 | youthclubs2 = [[Hamburger SV]] | years1 = 1960–1972 | clubs1 = [[Hamburger SV]] | caps1 = 347 | goals1 = 114 | years2 = 1972–1973 | clubs2 = [[Highlands Park FC]] | caps2 = | goals2 = | years3 = 1973–1974 | clubs3 = [[HSV Barmbek-Uhlenhorst]] | caps3 =18 | goals3 =3 | years4 = 1974–1975 | clubs4 = [[Highlands Park FC]] | caps4 = | goals4 = | years5 = 1976–1977 | clubs5 = [[London City (soccer club)|London City]] | caps5 = | goals5 = | nationalyears1 = 1960–1964 | nationalteam1 = [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] | nationalcaps1 = 11 | nationalgoals1 = 7 }}
'''Gert "Charly" Dörfel''' (born 18 September 1939 in [[Hamburg]]) is a retired [[Germany|German]] [[Association football|football]] player.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1971-72/10557/vereinsspieler_gert-doerfel.html | title = Dörfel, Gert | language = German | publisher = kicker.de | accessdate = 22 April 2011}}</ref>
== Playing career == Dörfel won the [[1960 German football championship|1960 West German championship]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hsv-history.de/doerfel.html|title=Gert 'Charly' Dörfel|newspaper=HSV-history.de|access-date=2017-02-25|language=de-DE}}</ref> and spent nine seasons in the [[Bundesliga]] after its introduction with [[Hamburger SV]], where he appeared in 224 matches and scored 58 goals.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://rsssf.com/players/chdoerfeldata.html | title = Gert 'Charly' Dörfel - Matches and Goals in Bundesliga | first = Matthias | last = Arnhold | date = 4 May 2017 | accessdate = 4 May 2017 | publisher = [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]}}</ref> In 1972, he went abroad to South Africa to play with [[Highlands Park F.C.]]. After one season in the [[National Professional Soccer League (South Africa)|National Professional Soccer League]] he returned to Germany to play with [[HSV Barmbek-Uhlenhorst]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teamdeutschland.net/players/d/gert-d%C3%B6rfel/|title=Gert Dörfel|website=www.teamdeutschland.net|language=fr-FR|access-date=2017-02-25}}</ref> Within a year he returned to South Africa, and went overseas to Canada in 1976 to play with [[London City Soccer Club|London City]] in the [[Canadian National Soccer League|National Soccer League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com/01cpsl9r.htm|title=Gauss looking ahead to brighter City future|last=Kernaghan|first=Jim|date=|website=www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com|publisher=London Free Press|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-02-25}}</ref>
== International career == He represented [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] 11 times,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/sport/legenden/Charly-Doerfel-Flankengott-und-Entertainer-,doerfel129.html|title=Charly Dörfel: Flankengott und Entertainer|last=NDR|website=www.ndr.de|language=de|access-date=2017-02-25}}</ref> including at the [[1962 FIFA World Cup]] qualifiers against [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] (scoring two goals) and [[Greece national football team|Greece]] (scoring one goal), the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]] qualifier against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]], and eight friendlies.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://rsssf.com/miscellaneous/chdoerfel-intl.html | title = Gert 'Charly' Dörfel - Goals in International Matches | first = Matthias | last = Arnhold | date = 4 May 2017 | accessdate = 4 May 2017 | publisher = [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]}}</ref>
== Personal life == His brother [[Bernd Dörfel]] also played for Germany. After retiring as a footballer, he worked for many years as a [[clown]] with engagements at among others [[Circus Krone]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/sport/legenden/doerfel129_page-2.html|title=Charly Dörfel: Flankengott und Entertainer (Seite 2)|last=NDR|website=www.ndr.de|language=de|access-date=2017-02-25}}</ref>
==Honours== * [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]] finalist: [[1967–68 European Cup Winners' Cup|1967–68]] * [[List of German football champions|German football championship]] winner: [[1960 German football championship|1960]] * [[DFB-Pokal]] winner: [[1962–63 DFB-Pokal|1962–63]] * [[DFB-Pokal]] finalist: [[1966–67 DFB-Pokal|1966–67]]
